00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:04.970
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C..

00:00:16.550 --> 00:00:17.850
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: Well,
thank you all for coming.

00:00:17.850 --> 00:00:19.150
I'm John Haskell.

00:00:19.150 --> 00:00:20.450
I'm the Director of
the Kluge Center here

00:00:20.450 --> 00:00:21.750
at the Library of Congress.

00:00:21.750 --> 00:00:25.060
And we together with
the Center for the book,

00:00:25.060 --> 00:00:29.920
represented by Guy Lamal-- I
can never pronounce your name.

00:00:29.920 --> 00:00:32.220
[Laughter] Help me with this.

00:00:33.730 --> 00:00:35.190
[Laughter] Guy, anyway,
is his name.

00:00:35.190 --> 00:00:37.370
Is, he, he and us
worked on this project,

00:00:37.370 --> 00:00:40.980
and we're glad you came
to see the program.

00:00:40.980 --> 00:00:46.260
The Kluge Center is, our mission
as established in the charter

00:00:46.260 --> 00:00:47.890
in 2000 is to, quote,

00:00:47.890 --> 00:00:49.610
"Reinvigorate the
interconnection

00:00:49.610 --> 00:00:51.150
between thought and action.

00:00:51.150 --> 00:00:54.080
Bridging the gap between
scholarship and policy-making."

00:00:54.080 --> 00:00:56.830
To that end we, we have
programs like this one.

00:00:56.830 --> 00:01:00.140
Where we bring, in this case,
one of our former chairs,

00:01:00.140 --> 00:01:04.490
former Kissinger
Chair, Bruce Jentleson.

00:01:04.490 --> 00:01:06.440
To talk about a book
that he was working

00:01:06.440 --> 00:01:07.740
on while he was at Kluge.

00:01:07.740 --> 00:01:09.610
We'll get into that
more shortly.

00:01:09.610 --> 00:01:11.500
Let me tell you a
little bit about Bruce.

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:14.500
He's Professor of Political
Science and Public Policy

00:01:14.500 --> 00:01:18.360
at the Sanford School of Public
Policy at Duke University.

00:01:18.360 --> 00:01:20.450
Bruce's degrees,
at the bachelor's

00:01:20.450 --> 00:01:23.760
and doctoral level are
from Cornell University.

00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:25.150
And he has a master's degree

00:01:25.150 --> 00:01:27.660
from the London School
of Economics.

00:01:27.660 --> 00:01:29.510
The current book
is The Peacemakers.

00:01:29.510 --> 00:01:31.490
Which is what we're going
to talk about today.

00:01:31.490 --> 00:01:35.140
Lessons in Leadership from
Twentieth Century Statesmen.

00:01:35.140 --> 00:01:38.000
That is coming out right
now, essentially, right?

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:39.300
Like today.

00:01:39.300 --> 00:01:40.600
You can get one afterward.

00:01:40.600 --> 00:01:42.330
And Bruce will sign it for you.

00:01:42.330 --> 00:01:44.920
He has a textbook called
American Foreign Policy that's

00:01:44.920 --> 00:01:46.350
in its fifth edition.

00:01:46.350 --> 00:01:48.660
Probably some of you have
had that assigned to you.

00:01:48.660 --> 00:01:50.210
And I'm sure you
read it carefully.

00:01:50.210 --> 00:01:52.050
He also wrote The
End of Arrogance:

00:01:52.050 --> 00:01:55.220
America in the Global
Competition of Ideas.

00:01:55.220 --> 00:01:57.940
And With Friends Like
These: Reagan, Bush,

00:01:57.940 --> 00:02:03.370
and Saddam: 1982 to 1990.

00:02:03.370 --> 00:02:06.350
Bruce is one of those
academics who, in his career,

00:02:06.350 --> 00:02:08.880
has done a lot in
the policy side.

00:02:08.880 --> 00:02:12.530
Which informs and, and,
and most of us think,

00:02:12.530 --> 00:02:14.000
here at the Kluge Center,
all of us think here

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:16.700
at the Kluge Center makes
one's scholarship better.

00:02:16.700 --> 00:02:18.070
He was Senior Advisor

00:02:18.070 --> 00:02:22.490
to the State Department
from 2009 to 2011.

00:02:22.490 --> 00:02:24.440
For the Obama Administration.

00:02:24.440 --> 00:02:27.550
And he served on
the 2012 campaign,

00:02:27.550 --> 00:02:30.860
National Security Advisory,
Advisory Steering Committee.

00:02:30.860 --> 00:02:33.730
He was a senior foreign
policy advisor

00:02:33.730 --> 00:02:36.840
to Vice President Gore
during the 2000 campaign.

00:02:36.840 --> 00:02:39.200
And he served in the Clinton
Administration State Department.

00:02:39.200 --> 00:02:41.700
And he also worked in
the United States Senate,

00:02:41.700 --> 00:02:44.570
both for Senator Al Gore,
when he was in the Senate.

00:02:44.570 --> 00:02:48.340
And also for Senator David
Durenberger who was a Republican

00:02:48.340 --> 00:02:50.960
from Minnesota many years ago.

00:02:50.960 --> 00:02:55.870
Bruce is co-founder with a
gentleman, Jim Goldgeier,

00:02:55.870 --> 00:02:57.920
who will be Kissinger
Chair come this fall.

00:02:57.920 --> 00:03:01.850
Of Bridging the Gap, which is a
policy promoting greater policy

00:03:01.850 --> 00:03:03.320
relevance among academics.

00:03:03.320 --> 00:03:05.620
We'll talk a little bit
more about that later.

00:03:05.620 --> 00:03:07.670
But let's dive into the
first question, Bruce.

00:03:07.670 --> 00:03:10.610
And I just want to know
why you wrote this book.

00:03:10.610 --> 00:03:11.910
&gt;&gt; Dr. Bruce Jentleson:
Well first of all,

00:03:11.910 --> 00:03:13.310
let me say thank you for the
invitation to be here today.

00:03:13.310 --> 00:03:14.740
To the sponsors.

00:03:14.740 --> 00:03:16.040
Special thank you
to the Kluge Center.

00:03:16.040 --> 00:03:18.700
I spent the 2015-'16
academic year here

00:03:18.700 --> 00:03:20.630
as the Kissinger Chair.

00:03:20.630 --> 00:03:22.880
There would be no book if it
was not for the opportunity

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:24.470
to do research while I was here.

00:03:24.470 --> 00:03:26.290
Thanks especially to Jay
McCullough who was head

00:03:26.290 --> 00:03:27.590
of Kluge at that point.

00:03:27.590 --> 00:03:30.870
When, when I applied
and was gracious enough

00:03:30.870 --> 00:03:32.170
to accept my application.

00:03:32.170 --> 00:03:34.760
So I, I really appreciate that.

00:03:34.760 --> 00:03:37.610
So you know a lot of the
work I've done, as John said,

00:03:37.610 --> 00:03:38.910
you know, in the policy world.

00:03:38.910 --> 00:03:40.940
As well as my academic
world work has been

00:03:40.940 --> 00:03:43.430
on you know deeply
intractable foreign policy

00:03:43.430 --> 00:03:45.070
international problems.

00:03:45.070 --> 00:03:47.090
I spent a number of years
working in the Middle East

00:03:47.090 --> 00:03:49.960
on various peace talks and
a variety of other issues.

00:03:49.960 --> 00:03:52.320
I worked on so-called
responsibility to protect

00:03:52.320 --> 00:03:54.690
and genocide pre, prevention.

00:03:54.690 --> 00:03:59.040
And this book deals with you
know many intractable problems.

00:03:59.040 --> 00:04:01.560
But I tried to focus on ones

00:04:01.560 --> 00:04:04.220
in which major breakthroughs
were made during the 20th

00:04:04.220 --> 00:04:07.050
century by a variety of types,
by a variety of leaders.

00:04:07.050 --> 00:04:08.860
So at one point I was
beginning to think

00:04:08.860 --> 00:04:11.830
that I was writing this book
as mental health exercise.

00:04:11.830 --> 00:04:14.900
To keep me thinking
about the positives.

00:04:14.900 --> 00:04:17.220
It's not about any
perfect pieces.

00:04:17.220 --> 00:04:20.370
None of these were, you
know, absolute piece

00:04:20.370 --> 00:04:21.670
that was fully enduring.

00:04:21.670 --> 00:04:24.420
That book would be very,
very short and thin.

00:04:24.420 --> 00:04:26.660
But I did decide
to finish it and,

00:04:26.660 --> 00:04:30.210
and then enjoy the mental
health benefits of talking

00:04:30.210 --> 00:04:31.510
about it to, to people.

00:04:31.510 --> 00:04:32.810
But it's very important,
I thought,

00:04:32.810 --> 00:04:35.590
to talk about when we see
these very difficult problems

00:04:35.590 --> 00:04:36.890
in the world.

00:04:36.890 --> 00:04:40.280
A variety of types for
both practical strategy

00:04:40.280 --> 00:04:42.050
and inspiration.

00:04:42.050 --> 00:04:43.850
To see where leaders
really were able

00:04:43.850 --> 00:04:45.590
to make major breakthroughs.

00:04:45.590 --> 00:04:50.620
And learn from that what we can
for the 21st century agenda.

00:04:50.620 --> 00:04:52.880
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: So
you have experience

00:04:52.880 --> 00:04:54.960
in both academics and in policy.

00:04:54.960 --> 00:04:58.130
How did that influence
the writing of this book?

00:04:58.130 --> 00:04:59.550
I mean, in, in the sense

00:04:59.550 --> 00:05:02.200
of how did you bring those
two together in this book?

00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:03.500
&gt;&gt; Dr. Bruce Jentleson:
So it's interesting.

00:05:03.500 --> 00:05:05.610
Those, you know, you know
John and others who have been

00:05:05.610 --> 00:05:10.250
through [inaudible]
and political science.

00:05:10.250 --> 00:05:12.180
You know, there's
very little emphasis

00:05:12.180 --> 00:05:14.920
on what they call the individual
level of analysis on leaders.

00:05:14.920 --> 00:05:16.540
It's about institutions.

00:05:16.540 --> 00:05:17.840
It's about processes.

00:05:17.840 --> 00:05:19.860
When you study international
relations,

00:05:19.860 --> 00:05:21.840
it's about you know
enduring concepts.

00:05:21.840 --> 00:05:23.740
Like balance of power,
national interest.

00:05:23.740 --> 00:05:25.230
As much of it should be.

00:05:25.230 --> 00:05:26.530
Indeed, put a number on it.

00:05:26.530 --> 00:05:29.490
Seventy to eighty
percent of what happens

00:05:29.490 --> 00:05:32.050
in international affairs, who
the leader is matters a little.

00:05:32.050 --> 00:05:34.050
But, but not fundamentally.

00:05:34.050 --> 00:05:38.290
In Washington, having spent a
lot of time inside the Beltway,

00:05:38.290 --> 00:05:40.880
not just Kluge Center but
the other positions I've had.

00:05:40.880 --> 00:05:44.120
Sometimes there can be like
too much emphasis on leaders.

00:05:44.120 --> 00:05:45.420
Who did what?

00:05:45.420 --> 00:05:46.720
What's the chemistry?

00:05:46.720 --> 00:05:48.020
You know, who winked at whom?

00:05:48.020 --> 00:05:49.320
Et cetera, et cetera.

00:05:49.320 --> 00:05:52.410
And so I was looking for sort of
a balance point between those.

00:05:52.410 --> 00:05:55.430
And, and one of the ways
I, I thought about it.

00:05:55.430 --> 00:05:58.930
I use an epigram from Isaiah
Berlin to start the book.

00:05:58.930 --> 00:06:01.110
Which is always a good
idea to quote Isaiah Berlin

00:06:01.110 --> 00:06:02.410
when you start a book.

00:06:02.410 --> 00:06:03.710
You can't go wrong.

00:06:03.710 --> 00:06:07.930
And, and he said, "At crucial
moments, at turning points,

00:06:07.930 --> 00:06:09.380
individuals in their decisions

00:06:09.380 --> 00:06:11.640
and acts can determine
the course of history."

00:06:11.640 --> 00:06:12.940
And that's really
what I look at.

00:06:12.940 --> 00:06:14.910
Crucial, crucial moments,
at turning points.

00:06:14.910 --> 00:06:16.210
Not day to day.

00:06:16.210 --> 00:06:17.990
Why I call the book
transformational moments,

00:06:17.990 --> 00:06:19.830
not just the transactional part.

00:06:19.830 --> 00:06:22.710
And I actually got a little bit
of inspiration from an article

00:06:22.710 --> 00:06:27.320
that some colleagues wrote about
so-called "bad guy leaders."

00:06:27.320 --> 00:06:28.830
And in that article, they, they,

00:06:28.830 --> 00:06:31.130
they looked at for
example Germany and Hitler.

00:06:31.130 --> 00:06:33.870
And said there's no question
that Germany was going

00:06:33.870 --> 00:06:36.490
to be unstable after
World War I.

00:06:36.490 --> 00:06:37.790
But the particular form

00:06:37.790 --> 00:06:40.470
that instability took
had an awful lot to do

00:06:40.470 --> 00:06:42.750
with Hitler as the leader.

00:06:42.750 --> 00:06:44.940
Similarly with Napoleon
after the French Revolution.

00:06:44.940 --> 00:06:46.240
France was going to be unstable.

00:06:46.240 --> 00:06:49.420
And so I tried to flip that
around and, and look at it

00:06:49.420 --> 00:06:50.890
from a positive point of view.

00:06:50.890 --> 00:06:54.700
And so I was really trying
to find a middle ground there

00:06:54.700 --> 00:06:56.650
about where leaders matter.

00:06:56.650 --> 00:06:59.780
And then to flesh out, you know,
a little bit of a framework

00:06:59.780 --> 00:07:02.870
of how they really matter and
what we could learn from that.

00:07:02.870 --> 00:07:05.430
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: So that when,
when I just saw the title,

00:07:05.430 --> 00:07:07.800
before the book was even
available, I thought.

00:07:07.800 --> 00:07:11.850
"I wonder what the criteria
are to be a peacemaker."

00:07:11.850 --> 00:07:14.250
I mean, like is there like
an entrance requirement?

00:07:14.250 --> 00:07:15.550
You know, what's
the, what's the,

00:07:15.550 --> 00:07:16.900
what are the qualifications?

00:07:16.900 --> 00:07:18.810
&gt;&gt; Dr. Bruce Jentleson: So one
of the fun things in the book.

00:07:18.810 --> 00:07:20.260
It's written very
much as, in the,

00:07:20.260 --> 00:07:22.070
in the publishing [inaudible]
they call it "trade book."

00:07:22.070 --> 00:07:25.370
It's not just written for
academics and policy wonks.

00:07:25.370 --> 00:07:27.480
But it's really for broad
audiences who have interest

00:07:27.480 --> 00:07:29.150
in what's going on in the world.

00:07:29.150 --> 00:07:32.490
And so if I was really savvy,
I'd have a social media game

00:07:32.490 --> 00:07:34.240
out there now with
the book, right?

00:07:34.240 --> 00:07:37.320
For people to choose their
own 20th century peacemaker,

00:07:37.320 --> 00:07:38.620
peacemaker.

00:07:38.620 --> 00:07:41.870
So we do say, so I, I, when
I thought about what I mean

00:07:41.870 --> 00:07:44.020
by peacemakers and
global peace and security.

00:07:44.020 --> 00:07:47.020
I break it into five
different categories.

00:07:47.020 --> 00:07:50.080
One is the major
powers, geopolitics.

00:07:50.080 --> 00:07:52.900
Because conflicts by major
powers historically have been a

00:07:52.900 --> 00:07:54.200
principle cause of war.

00:07:54.200 --> 00:07:56.980
And rapprochement between
major powers has been crucial

00:07:56.980 --> 00:07:58.280
to peace.

00:07:58.280 --> 00:08:01.450
Secondly, building
international institutions.

00:08:01.450 --> 00:08:04.820
Third, reconciling the
politics of identity in terms

00:08:04.820 --> 00:08:06.900
of conflicts that are core.

00:08:06.900 --> 00:08:08.400
Based on issues of identity.

00:08:08.400 --> 00:08:10.610
Fourth is advancing
freedom and human rights.

00:08:10.610 --> 00:08:13.370
And fifth is fostering
global sustainability.

00:08:13.370 --> 00:08:15.310
And so at each of those areas,

00:08:15.310 --> 00:08:17.550
I try to have representative
cases.

00:08:17.550 --> 00:08:21.380
And the criteria
that I use are one,

00:08:21.380 --> 00:08:24.440
that it's about transformational
statesmanship.

00:08:24.440 --> 00:08:25.970
Not just transactional.

00:08:25.970 --> 00:08:29.050
It's efforts to really make
a breakthrough in the trans,

00:08:29.050 --> 00:08:31.080
in the intractable problems.

00:08:31.080 --> 00:08:34.860
Secondly, and here I
confess as I was coming in,

00:08:34.860 --> 00:08:37.110
I saw that there's a
Baseball Americana exhibit

00:08:37.110 --> 00:08:38.660
in the Jefferson
Building in June

00:08:38.660 --> 00:08:39.960
which I've got to come back for.

00:08:39.960 --> 00:08:41.780
Because I'm, I'm a
total baseball fan.

00:08:41.780 --> 00:08:45.030
And anybody that you know
follows the Moneyball,

00:08:45.030 --> 00:08:47.720
there's this statistic
called wins

00:08:47.720 --> 00:08:49.570
against replacement
player or WARP.

00:08:49.570 --> 00:08:53.160
Which is how many wins does this
particular shortstop contribute

00:08:53.160 --> 00:08:54.460
to his team.

00:08:54.460 --> 00:08:56.150
You know, calculated
against every other shortstop

00:08:56.150 --> 00:08:58.400
in baseball, and
there's a fancy formula.

00:08:58.400 --> 00:09:00.510
And so I call mine
"statesmanship Moneyball."

00:09:00.510 --> 00:09:03.640
Alright? And I don't really
have a statistical formula.

00:09:03.640 --> 00:09:06.490
I just base it on the basis of
the argument and the evidence.

00:09:06.490 --> 00:09:09.570
And, and try to say that
this leader made choices

00:09:09.570 --> 00:09:11.830
that another leader in that
situation wouldn't have made.

00:09:11.830 --> 00:09:13.750
For example, Gorba-- there's
a chapter on Gorbachev.

00:09:13.750 --> 00:09:15.140
And I strongly argue
against those

00:09:15.140 --> 00:09:17.070
that say any Soviet
leader would have had

00:09:17.070 --> 00:09:18.660
to make the choices he did.

00:09:18.660 --> 00:09:20.590
And so that's the
second criteria.

00:09:20.590 --> 00:09:24.980
Is it really something that,
that the particular had a set

00:09:24.980 --> 00:09:27.180
of choices and political skills?

00:09:27.180 --> 00:09:30.620
And the third one is what I call
impact had, not position held.

00:09:30.620 --> 00:09:33.690
And there I broaden the
concept of statesmanship.

00:09:33.690 --> 00:09:35.820
So it's not only, we'll
see as we go along,

00:09:35.820 --> 00:09:38.370
about presidents
or prime ministers.

00:09:38.370 --> 00:09:40.700
Secretaries of state,
foreign ministers.

00:09:40.700 --> 00:09:44.690
There's some chapters in there
that are about leaders of NGOs.

00:09:44.690 --> 00:09:48.870
There's some chapters in there
that are about social movements.

00:09:48.870 --> 00:09:50.170
In which they did things

00:09:50.170 --> 00:09:52.960
that governments were either
unable or unwilling to do.

00:09:52.960 --> 00:09:55.190
And again, as we think
about the 21st century,

00:09:55.190 --> 00:09:56.670
we're going to see
even more of that.

00:09:56.670 --> 00:09:59.220
So those were kind of
the criteria I used.

00:09:59.220 --> 00:10:01.340
And you know we have a
discussion, I'd love to hear,

00:10:01.340 --> 00:10:03.620
"why don't you have
so-and-so and so-and-so?"

00:10:03.620 --> 00:10:06.250
And that, that's what kind of
makes, but, but I was very clear

00:10:06.250 --> 00:10:07.630
that these were representative
cases.

00:10:07.630 --> 00:10:10.300
Not necessarily comprehensive
in closing the book so.

00:10:10.300 --> 00:10:11.600
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: It's
funny, there's, you know,

00:10:11.600 --> 00:10:12.900
sometimes statesman
are considered

00:10:12.900 --> 00:10:14.200
to be Commissioner of Baseball.

00:10:14.200 --> 00:10:15.500
Like George Mitchell.

00:10:15.500 --> 00:10:17.460
Might not have peace in
Ireland if he had gone

00:10:17.460 --> 00:10:18.760
that route, I don't know.

00:10:18.760 --> 00:10:22.950
But so the one of the ones that,
that, that you, that you count

00:10:22.950 --> 00:10:26.790
as a peacemaker who would
certainly be controversial

00:10:26.790 --> 00:10:29.390
in some corridors would
be Henry Kissinger.

00:10:29.390 --> 00:10:32.540
So you know as the
former Kissinger Chair,

00:10:32.540 --> 00:10:35.040
perhaps you could speak to that.

00:10:35.040 --> 00:10:36.340
&gt;&gt; Dr. Bruce Jentleson:
There are no strings tied

00:10:36.340 --> 00:10:38.170
to the Kissinger Chair that
are to be included in the book.

00:10:38.170 --> 00:10:40.150
[Laughter] I had a
distinguished fellowship

00:10:40.150 --> 00:10:41.580
at the Woodrow Wilson
Center, too.

00:10:41.580 --> 00:10:44.650
In fact, my chapter on Wilson
is highly, highly critical

00:10:44.650 --> 00:10:47.390
of Wilson in ways that I didn't
even realize before I started

00:10:47.390 --> 00:10:48.690
doing the research.

00:10:48.690 --> 00:10:51.620
So another criteria is it's
not about the overall record.

00:10:51.620 --> 00:10:55.180
It's about particular
areas of statesmanship.

00:10:55.180 --> 00:10:57.120
Kissinger is in the book
along with Zhou Enlai

00:10:57.120 --> 00:10:59.250
for the U.S.-China opening.

00:10:59.250 --> 00:11:03.290
Not for Vietnam or for other
things that I acknowledge

00:11:03.290 --> 00:11:04.590
that these are areas that.

00:11:04.590 --> 00:11:07.490
You know, that I
personally disagreed with.

00:11:07.490 --> 00:11:11.630
But I feel like we need to learn
things from leaders, you know,

00:11:11.630 --> 00:11:13.230
in, in, rather than everybody's

00:11:13.230 --> 00:11:14.700
in this basket called
"a great leader."

00:11:14.700 --> 00:11:16.930
And this basket called
"a flawed leader."

00:11:16.930 --> 00:11:18.660
We need to try to
learn from a variety.

00:11:18.660 --> 00:11:22.300
And so that, that really
looks at the breakthrough

00:11:22.300 --> 00:11:24.420
that was made in
U.S.-China relations.

00:11:24.420 --> 00:11:28.130
Sometimes when we look
back at history, we say,

00:11:28.130 --> 00:11:30.410
"Well of course they, they
made a breakthrough back then.

00:11:30.410 --> 00:11:33.270
You know, they were all, they
had a mutual sort of enemy

00:11:33.270 --> 00:11:34.900
or adversary in the
Soviet Union."

00:11:34.900 --> 00:11:37.430
But if you go back, and if
you had gone to Las Vegas

00:11:37.430 --> 00:11:38.730
or [inaudible] if
you're in London.

00:11:38.730 --> 00:11:41.930
In early 1971 and said,
"I'd like to place a bet

00:11:41.930 --> 00:11:45.010
that the United States and,
and Red China," as we used

00:11:45.010 --> 00:11:46.390
to call it in those days.

00:11:46.390 --> 00:11:48.230
"Are going to you
know have some sort

00:11:48.230 --> 00:11:49.560
of rapprochement sort
of relationship."

00:11:49.560 --> 00:11:51.600
We all could have been
wealthier than we are.

00:11:51.600 --> 00:11:53.480
And so, I, I look into that.

00:11:53.480 --> 00:11:54.780
I did have the opportunity

00:11:54.780 --> 00:11:57.720
to interview Kissinger
for that research.

00:11:57.720 --> 00:12:00.230
And one really, when you
do this kind of research,

00:12:00.230 --> 00:12:02.510
a lot of the documents
are declassified.

00:12:02.510 --> 00:12:04.380
So I had the documentary record.

00:12:04.380 --> 00:12:07.200
I had work that was
done by other scholars,

00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:08.840
a whole variety of things.

00:12:08.840 --> 00:12:11.530
But you get the color when
you do the interviews.

00:12:11.530 --> 00:12:14.160
And I'll give you
one example of that.

00:12:14.160 --> 00:12:16.910
There'd been, when Kissinger
first meets Zhou Enlai

00:12:16.910 --> 00:12:18.950
in July 1971.

00:12:18.950 --> 00:12:22.320
And what was called the
secret Operation Marco Polo.

00:12:22.320 --> 00:12:23.620
They had this great name for it.

00:12:23.620 --> 00:12:24.920
[Laughter]

00:12:24.920 --> 00:12:26.670
Although you would have thought
if somebody heard the name,

00:12:26.670 --> 00:12:27.970
they would have thought
it might have something

00:12:27.970 --> 00:12:29.270
to do with China, right?

00:12:29.270 --> 00:12:31.420
And the first thing it says
is he walks in and he puts

00:12:31.420 --> 00:12:33.540
out his hand to shake
Zhou Enlai's hand.

00:12:33.540 --> 00:12:34.840
So I asked Kissinger about that.

00:12:34.840 --> 00:12:36.180
Because he couldn't quite tell
from the documentary record.

00:12:36.180 --> 00:12:37.480
And he tells this story.

00:12:37.480 --> 00:12:40.570
He says, "You know,
in back in 1955.

00:12:40.570 --> 00:12:43.060
At the Geneva Convention

00:12:43.060 --> 00:12:45.450
after the French were
defeated in Vietnam.

00:12:45.450 --> 00:12:49.300
And Vietnam was being broken up
and the rest of Southeast Asia.

00:12:49.300 --> 00:12:50.640
John Foster Dulles, you know,

00:12:50.640 --> 00:12:53.710
very hawkish American
Secretary of State.

00:12:53.710 --> 00:12:57.350
Soviet Foreign Minister Molotov,
you know, he of the cocktail.

00:12:57.350 --> 00:12:59.190
And Zhou Enlai, the Chinese
Foreign Minister were there.

00:12:59.190 --> 00:13:02.130
And Dulles showed up and
he shook Molotov's hand,

00:13:02.130 --> 00:13:04.050
but he wouldn't shake
Zhou Enlai's hand.

00:13:04.050 --> 00:13:05.350
Again, this was Red China.

00:13:05.350 --> 00:13:06.650
And you read some of
the things at the time.

00:13:06.650 --> 00:13:08.150
And we thought they
were much worse

00:13:08.150 --> 00:13:09.680
than even the Soviet Union.

00:13:09.680 --> 00:13:12.370
And so Kissinger, and
he says, "It wasn't me."

00:13:12.370 --> 00:13:15.370
It was some China experts
he had on his staff,

00:13:15.370 --> 00:13:19.390
said that this is a real
gesture of building trust.

00:13:19.390 --> 00:13:21.170
And it really meant a lot.

00:13:21.170 --> 00:13:23.600
As they got to know each other,

00:13:23.600 --> 00:13:26.120
Zhou Enlai at a later meeting
told Kissinger how much

00:13:26.120 --> 00:13:27.420
that meant to him.

00:13:27.420 --> 00:13:30.000
You know? And that had really
stayed with him for what?

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:31.540
Sixteen, seventeen years.

00:13:31.540 --> 00:13:34.140
And so this kind of thing that
is in the book that you pick

00:13:34.140 --> 00:13:35.710
up the color from
the interviews.

00:13:35.710 --> 00:13:38.510
That gives you a sense of
this really being Kissinger

00:13:38.510 --> 00:13:39.810
at his best.

00:13:39.810 --> 00:13:41.400
You know, great power
of statesmanship

00:13:41.400 --> 00:13:43.370
which was very different
than some other eras.

00:13:43.370 --> 00:13:44.670
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: So
you know, you can get,

00:13:44.670 --> 00:13:46.300
you can see why he was,
why this, you know,

00:13:46.300 --> 00:13:47.760
can be considered
transformational.

00:13:47.760 --> 00:13:49.440
What, what happened with China.

00:13:49.440 --> 00:13:53.400
Why was Kissinger, you know,
in your Wins Above Replacement?

00:13:53.400 --> 00:13:54.700
You know, comparison.

00:13:54.700 --> 00:13:56.790
Why was he important here?

00:13:56.790 --> 00:13:58.300
&gt;&gt; Dr. Bruce Jentleson: So
I talk about it, you know,

00:13:58.300 --> 00:13:59.600
why not Nix-- , Nix-- , I mean.

00:13:59.600 --> 00:14:02.170
And every story I tell's not
just about a single individual.

00:14:02.170 --> 00:14:03.470
Others come in.

00:14:03.470 --> 00:14:05.660
It's not hero worship, but
I focus on the individual

00:14:05.660 --> 00:14:08.270
that I think was that
statesmanship Moneyball.

00:14:08.270 --> 00:14:10.760
So my little one-liner is
Nixon and Al got the opera.

00:14:10.760 --> 00:14:13.590
And Kissinger and Zhou
Enlai did the statesmanship.

00:14:13.590 --> 00:14:16.440
The statesmanship
was very intricate.

00:14:16.440 --> 00:14:22.170
And they spent seventeen hours
in those first set of meetings.

00:14:22.170 --> 00:14:25.360
Basically in one-on-ones
with translators.

00:14:25.360 --> 00:14:26.900
And maybe with one aid.

00:14:26.900 --> 00:14:29.870
And they had an enormous
amount to work through.

00:14:29.870 --> 00:14:33.270
And the essence of it was one

00:14:33.270 --> 00:14:35.920
of the United States' main
motivations is we wanted more

00:14:35.920 --> 00:14:37.650
help from China on Vietnam.

00:14:37.650 --> 00:14:39.560
Because the Soviets
weren't giving it.

00:14:39.560 --> 00:14:41.660
And China wanted a
lot from us on Taiwan.

00:14:41.660 --> 00:14:43.530
That was the transactional
point.

00:14:43.530 --> 00:14:45.740
We got less on Vietnam
than we wanted.

00:14:45.740 --> 00:14:47.040
But we got some.

00:14:47.040 --> 00:14:48.340
They got less on Taiwan
in the moment they wanted.

00:14:48.340 --> 00:14:49.640
They got some.

00:14:49.640 --> 00:14:51.560
And there's a statement
that, that Zhou Enlai makes

00:14:51.560 --> 00:14:54.580
in which he basically says,
well, I'll interpret this.

00:14:54.580 --> 00:14:55.890
He says, "Conventional thinking

00:14:55.890 --> 00:14:57.340
about statesmanship
is you've got to work

00:14:57.340 --> 00:14:58.640
out the transactional.

00:14:58.640 --> 00:15:02.160
And sort of the aggregate sum of
this deal and that deal is going

00:15:02.160 --> 00:15:04.870
to lead to change in
the relationship."

00:15:04.870 --> 00:15:07.220
And he actually says you
know, you really need to start

00:15:07.220 --> 00:15:08.520
with the transformational.

00:15:08.520 --> 00:15:09.820
There needs to be a sense

00:15:09.820 --> 00:15:11.120
that the relationship
is transforming.

00:15:11.120 --> 00:15:12.580
The trust has been building up.

00:15:12.580 --> 00:15:14.240
Whatever concessions
were made that will lead

00:15:14.240 --> 00:15:16.470
to other progress
in the relationship.

00:15:16.470 --> 00:15:19.310
And that the transformational
actually has to precede

00:15:19.310 --> 00:15:22.090
or at accompany the
transactional.

00:15:22.090 --> 00:15:23.420
Which we can talk
about in relation

00:15:23.420 --> 00:15:24.720
to any number of things.

00:15:24.720 --> 00:15:27.050
You know, U.S.-Korea
or Iran or whatever.

00:15:27.050 --> 00:15:29.740
But and so the way they
worked out the statesmanship

00:15:29.740 --> 00:15:31.040
and I go into some detail.

00:15:31.040 --> 00:15:33.470
Not as much as if it was
a straight academic book.

00:15:33.470 --> 00:15:36.840
There are any number of points
where it could have broken down.

00:15:36.840 --> 00:15:39.980
Nixon and Mao were absolutely
necessary for the politics.

00:15:39.980 --> 00:15:43.560
But I felt like that, that there
was more of a story to tell

00:15:43.560 --> 00:15:44.860
about the statesmanship.

00:15:44.860 --> 00:15:47.510
And so make them, and
that's the pair chapter.

00:15:47.510 --> 00:15:52.070
Where if you like, it's a
50/50, you know, giving credit.

00:15:52.070 --> 00:15:54.780
Because the both of
them were, were crucial.

00:15:54.780 --> 00:15:56.080
Not just Kissinger.

00:15:56.080 --> 00:15:58.620
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: So how did
Aung San Suu Kyi qualify?

00:15:58.620 --> 00:16:00.530
How did, how did
she make the grade?

00:16:00.530 --> 00:16:02.110
&gt;&gt; Dr. Bruce Jentleson: That's
really an interesting story.

00:16:02.110 --> 00:16:05.430
That chapter's titled
"A Cautionary Tale."

00:16:05.430 --> 00:16:06.860
And we, I'd started writing it.

00:16:06.860 --> 00:16:09.080
Actually, I working it
out when I was here.

00:16:09.080 --> 00:16:10.940
About the role she
played in Burma,

00:16:10.940 --> 00:16:14.060
Myanmar, from 1988 to 2015.

00:16:14.060 --> 00:16:15.500
Which again was quite
extraordinary.

00:16:15.500 --> 00:16:18.270
An enormous amount of
personal and moral courage.

00:16:18.270 --> 00:16:20.770
A leadership that pretty
much only she could provide

00:16:20.770 --> 00:16:22.330
with her heritage being
the daughter of one

00:16:22.330 --> 00:16:23.630
of the founders of the country.

00:16:23.630 --> 00:16:27.020
And a whole variety
of other factors.

00:16:27.020 --> 00:16:29.920
And then as we were finishing
the book last summer.

00:16:29.920 --> 00:16:33.670
There were Rohingya
genocides taking place.

00:16:33.670 --> 00:16:36.450
And you're getting articles
like from Nicholas Kristof

00:16:36.450 --> 00:16:40.800
about you know seeing a Nobel
Peace Prize winner you know not

00:16:40.800 --> 00:16:42.770
necessarily doing
this military-wise.

00:16:42.770 --> 00:16:45.510
But at minimum, being complicit.

00:16:45.510 --> 00:16:46.810
So my editor [inaudible] and I.

00:16:46.810 --> 00:16:48.110
I called him.

00:16:48.110 --> 00:16:49.410
I said, "I wonder if we
should pull the chapter."

00:16:49.410 --> 00:16:51.410
We actually had a couple other
chapter, couple of chapters

00:16:51.410 --> 00:16:54.300
that we didn't include because
we were looking at length.

00:16:54.300 --> 00:16:55.700
And I give him credit.

00:16:55.700 --> 00:16:57.110
He said, "You know,
let's think about this.

00:16:57.110 --> 00:17:00.490
The whole theme of the
book is draw lessons

00:17:00.490 --> 00:17:03.490
from where leaders had skills
and where they didn't."

00:17:03.490 --> 00:17:06.270
And there actually was
a pattern emerging.

00:17:06.270 --> 00:17:07.610
There's a chapter on Lech Walesa

00:17:07.610 --> 00:17:10.700
who was a terrible
President in Poland.

00:17:10.700 --> 00:17:13.380
But was an extraordinary leader
of the Polish Revolution.

00:17:13.380 --> 00:17:15.460
There's a chapter on Gandhi.

00:17:15.460 --> 00:17:17.840
And his role in,
in anti-colonialism

00:17:17.840 --> 00:17:19.140
and Indian independence.

00:17:19.140 --> 00:17:20.440
He was assassinated.

00:17:20.440 --> 00:17:21.810
But nobody ever thought
he could be a leader

00:17:21.810 --> 00:17:23.110
in government, right?

00:17:23.110 --> 00:17:25.980
And so the pattern that was
emerging was certain skill sets

00:17:25.980 --> 00:17:27.860
helped bring certain
kinds of change.

00:17:27.860 --> 00:17:30.090
And they don't necessarily
carry over to,

00:17:30.090 --> 00:17:32.500
to consolidating,
institutionalizing.

00:17:32.500 --> 00:17:34.850
So you know, did a little
bit of reframing it.

00:17:34.850 --> 00:17:37.270
And, and made very clear what we
were saying and what we weren't.

00:17:37.270 --> 00:17:39.230
We were concerned
some people might say,

00:17:39.230 --> 00:17:40.530
"How could she possibly
be in the book?"

00:17:40.530 --> 00:17:43.140
And I, I understand that
opinion and respect it.

00:17:43.140 --> 00:17:45.080
[Inaudible] Roger Collin,

00:17:45.080 --> 00:17:48.860
New York Times columnist wrote
a column that also came out.

00:17:48.860 --> 00:17:51.090
And I've known him for a while
while I was thinking about this.

00:17:51.090 --> 00:17:54.250
And he said, "We in the West
have a tendency to either idol,

00:17:54.250 --> 00:17:56.430
idealize or demonize people.

00:17:56.430 --> 00:17:58.730
And we need to break
out of that."

00:17:58.730 --> 00:18:00.290
And so that's the essence

00:18:00.290 --> 00:18:02.660
of that chapter is
the cautionary tale.

00:18:02.660 --> 00:18:04.080
Of both dimensions.

00:18:04.080 --> 00:18:06.010
And we felt it was
important to keep it in.

00:18:06.010 --> 00:18:07.950
And the same way
of Woodrow Wilson

00:18:07.950 --> 00:18:10.730
in for what his failures
were, not his successes.

00:18:10.730 --> 00:18:12.030
Even with what was happening.

00:18:12.030 --> 00:18:14.140
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: So,
so you touched on this,

00:18:14.140 --> 00:18:15.440
the next question
I have for you.

00:18:15.440 --> 00:18:16.740
You touched on this
a minute before.

00:18:16.740 --> 00:18:18.340
So I'm going to try
to pin you down.

00:18:18.340 --> 00:18:20.730
What's your position
on, you know,

00:18:20.730 --> 00:18:22.580
people have the age-old
question.

00:18:22.580 --> 00:18:26.280
Is it that leaders make history
or history makes leaders?

00:18:26.280 --> 00:18:27.860
&gt;&gt; Dr. Bruce Jentleson:
Yeah, and that's-- .

00:18:27.860 --> 00:18:29.160
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: It's
hard to say, you know.

00:18:29.160 --> 00:18:31.230
But, but you brought
it up so I want to-- .

00:18:31.230 --> 00:18:32.530
&gt;&gt; Dr. Bruce Jentleson: I did.

00:18:32.530 --> 00:18:33.830
And, and going back
to the academic train.

00:18:33.830 --> 00:18:35.430
I, I'd given a couple papers
you know related to this

00:18:35.430 --> 00:18:37.560
where I fleshed this out more.

00:18:37.560 --> 00:18:39.220
And there's a lot of
footnotes in there,

00:18:39.220 --> 00:18:41.720
some of the literature on this.

00:18:41.720 --> 00:18:45.580
The basic formulation I use
is what I call the three C's.

00:18:45.580 --> 00:18:50.510
The constraints that any
leader faces in making change.

00:18:50.510 --> 00:18:55.630
The conducive conditions
that they may have.

00:18:55.630 --> 00:18:58.560
But then the domain of choice
that's with the leader.

00:18:58.560 --> 00:19:00.430
And so that's that
middle ground.

00:19:00.430 --> 00:19:03.660
It acknowledges that there
may be conducive conditions.

00:19:03.660 --> 00:19:06.790
Like in the Kissinger Zhou Enlai
case, the fact that you know,

00:19:06.790 --> 00:19:09.100
Sino-Soviet relations
were deeply strained.

00:19:09.100 --> 00:19:10.950
And we were looking
for leverage as we went

00:19:10.950 --> 00:19:12.810
into the detente negotiations.

00:19:12.810 --> 00:19:14.700
So this was a conducive
condition.

00:19:14.700 --> 00:19:16.150
The same time there were
enormous constraints.

00:19:16.150 --> 00:19:19.220
The China lobby was hugely
powerful in this country.

00:19:19.220 --> 00:19:21.460
And China had just come out
of the cultural revolution

00:19:21.460 --> 00:19:23.820
and Mao wasn't convinced
he wanted this.

00:19:23.820 --> 00:19:26.220
But that domain of choice.

00:19:26.220 --> 00:19:30.500
And when that domain of
choice really is decisive is

00:19:30.500 --> 00:19:33.880
where I feel the focus on
leaders is, is really helpful.

00:19:33.880 --> 00:19:37.600
And, and so everybody
in the book.

00:19:37.600 --> 00:19:41.350
And I, I kind of taken on about
the whole you know, you know,

00:19:41.350 --> 00:19:44.050
was this really inevitable,
if we get academic with,

00:19:44.050 --> 00:19:46.020
the dependent variable,
you know?

00:19:46.020 --> 00:19:48.230
But that's really, I think
there's a middle ground there.

00:19:48.230 --> 00:19:49.530
That goes on.

00:19:49.530 --> 00:19:52.470
And again, I think we inside
the Beltway maybe get too much

00:19:52.470 --> 00:19:53.770
into the, you know.

00:19:53.770 --> 00:19:55.480
Everything about
you know the leader.

00:19:55.480 --> 00:19:58.760
And the academic world so,
so that was the effort.

00:19:58.760 --> 00:20:01.640
And you know bringing
some of the work back

00:20:01.640 --> 00:20:02.940
into the academic world.

00:20:02.940 --> 00:20:04.560
I'm trying to get
people to start thinking

00:20:04.560 --> 00:20:06.140
about how they can
pay more attention

00:20:06.140 --> 00:20:07.440
to the role the leaders have

00:20:07.440 --> 00:20:09.640
and not just the broad
things that you can model.

00:20:09.640 --> 00:20:10.940
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: Yeah, and,

00:20:10.940 --> 00:20:13.060
and you know presidential
historians the,

00:20:13.060 --> 00:20:17.390
maybe the greatest one, it's
about persuasion and choice.

00:20:17.390 --> 00:20:19.750
And you don't ex-- obviously,
I mean, persuasion's a part

00:20:19.750 --> 00:20:21.540
of what you're looking at
with these people as well.

00:20:21.540 --> 00:20:22.840
&gt;&gt; Dr. Bruce Jentleson:
I do, I do.

00:20:22.840 --> 00:20:24.140
The framework I develop is what,

00:20:24.140 --> 00:20:25.560
what I call the who,
why, how, what?

00:20:25.560 --> 00:20:27.900
Who are these people
as individuals?

00:20:27.900 --> 00:20:29.400
You know, not getting
super Freudian,

00:20:29.400 --> 00:20:32.680
but what were their
qualities as individuals?

00:20:32.680 --> 00:20:34.200
That, that led them.

00:20:34.200 --> 00:20:36.000
Yitzhak Rabin is in the
book in a chapter called

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:37.660
"Soldier's Peacemaker."

00:20:37.660 --> 00:20:39.170
You know, what were
his qualities that led

00:20:39.170 --> 00:20:41.400
from his transformation of
the Minister of Defense?

00:20:41.400 --> 00:20:43.880
Who as he said was breaking
knuckles during the First

00:20:43.880 --> 00:20:46.740
Intifada to somebody that
really had a vision for peace?

00:20:46.740 --> 00:20:49.160
With the Palestinians and
took it pretty far before he

00:20:49.160 --> 00:20:50.600
was assassinated.

00:20:50.600 --> 00:20:52.660
So who are these individuals?

00:20:52.660 --> 00:20:55.100
And many of them, you don't
really see these leadership

00:20:55.100 --> 00:20:56.400
qualities from the beginning.

00:20:56.400 --> 00:20:59.310
At the end I talk about you
know kind of runs against the,

00:20:59.310 --> 00:21:02.610
you know, the resume,
the political consultant.

00:21:02.610 --> 00:21:03.910
Let me look at the
things on the resume.

00:21:03.910 --> 00:21:06.510
They, you know, it's sort
of person and moment.

00:21:06.510 --> 00:21:07.810
Why did they do what they did?

00:21:07.810 --> 00:21:10.330
What was the vision
that brought them to try

00:21:10.330 --> 00:21:12.630
to take the risks
of these changes?

00:21:12.630 --> 00:21:15.310
And that they used to get
people to buy into it?

00:21:15.310 --> 00:21:16.610
Change is a scary thing.

00:21:16.610 --> 00:21:20.000
And how did they
provide people a sense

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:22.810
of that the current context
needed to be changed.

00:21:22.810 --> 00:21:27.070
Whether it's Mandela or Rabin
or [inaudible] or others.

00:21:27.070 --> 00:21:28.580
And then how did
they go about it?

00:21:28.580 --> 00:21:29.880
And that's where
there's this mix

00:21:29.880 --> 00:21:31.890
of ideas and political skills.

00:21:31.890 --> 00:21:34.650
And some of the limits, Rabin,
for example [inaudible] both.

00:21:34.650 --> 00:21:36.200
I give him an awful
lot of credit.

00:21:36.200 --> 00:21:39.000
But I talk about where his
political skills failed him.

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:40.340
Same with Gorbachev.

00:21:40.340 --> 00:21:41.640
You know, that he didn't, he,

00:21:41.640 --> 00:21:43.300
his political skills
were really failing him

00:21:43.300 --> 00:21:44.600
in those last couple of years.

00:21:44.600 --> 00:21:47.400
And consolidating and
taking care of his base.

00:21:47.400 --> 00:21:49.280
But it's, so it's
a mix, I think,

00:21:49.280 --> 00:21:51.570
of the two biggest
qualities of personal capital

00:21:51.570 --> 00:21:53.850
that people bring to this.

00:21:53.850 --> 00:21:56.160
That gives people a sense
that they are authentic.

00:21:56.160 --> 00:21:58.380
In Aung San Suu Kyi's case

00:21:58.380 --> 00:22:00.640
and Mandela's case
and [inaudible] case.

00:22:00.640 --> 00:22:01.940
And political skills.

00:22:01.940 --> 00:22:04.460
And the what is what did they
achieve and what didn't they?

00:22:04.460 --> 00:22:06.590
And again, what can we,
what can we learn from both?

00:22:06.590 --> 00:22:08.380
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: So you
mention there, you have to,

00:22:08.380 --> 00:22:11.080
a leader has to adjust
to change.

00:22:11.080 --> 00:22:12.380
Change is inevitable.

00:22:12.380 --> 00:22:15.720
But the communications
change is radical these days

00:22:15.720 --> 00:22:17.020
with social media.

00:22:17.020 --> 00:22:20.590
Is, is what does that do
to a leader's capacity?

00:22:20.590 --> 00:22:21.960
&gt;&gt; Dr. Bruce Jentleson: So let
me just really quickly pull

00:22:21.960 --> 00:22:23.960
out something I start
the epilogue with,

00:22:23.960 --> 00:22:25.500
if I can find it quickly.

00:22:25.500 --> 00:22:26.800
It speaks to that.

00:22:26.800 --> 00:22:30.830
So this is a quote that
I'm just going to read.

00:22:30.830 --> 00:22:33.970
"For our everyday life
is becoming so saturated

00:22:33.970 --> 00:22:36.930
with the tremendous power
of mass communications.

00:22:36.930 --> 00:22:39.940
Our political life is becoming
so expensive, so mechanized,

00:22:39.940 --> 00:22:42.860
and so dominated by
professional politicians

00:22:42.860 --> 00:22:44.620
and public relations men.

00:22:44.620 --> 00:22:45.920
That the idealist who dreams

00:22:45.920 --> 00:22:47.890
of independent statesmanship
is really awakened

00:22:47.890 --> 00:22:50.510
by the necessities of
election and accomplishment."

00:22:50.510 --> 00:22:53.320
That's from John Kennedy and
Profiles of Courage in 1956.

00:22:53.320 --> 00:22:55.660
And, and the book is actually
a little bit [inaudible]

00:22:55.660 --> 00:22:56.960
than Profiles in Courage.

00:22:56.960 --> 00:22:58.520
But it's, you know, not
just American Senators.

00:22:58.520 --> 00:23:01.050
It's international
leaders, it's not domestic.

00:23:01.050 --> 00:23:05.210
And you know so he's writing
that in 1956, you know.

00:23:05.210 --> 00:23:06.720
So it wasn't just today.

00:23:06.720 --> 00:23:08.580
There's no question
that social media--

00:23:08.580 --> 00:23:10.180
I know from my time you know

00:23:10.180 --> 00:23:11.930
in the foreign policy
world in Washington.

00:23:11.930 --> 00:23:16.340
You know, the, you know the, the
need to make decisions quickly.

00:23:16.340 --> 00:23:17.730
You know? God only knows

00:23:17.730 --> 00:23:21.050
if the Cuban Missile Crisis
had occurred with social media.

00:23:21.050 --> 00:23:24.770
And their ability to keep
control of information

00:23:24.770 --> 00:23:26.070
to a great extent then.

00:23:26.070 --> 00:23:27.370
That has complicated it.

00:23:27.370 --> 00:23:30.600
But I, I, I try to do a
push, not only in the book

00:23:30.600 --> 00:23:31.900
but in some of my other work.

00:23:31.900 --> 00:23:34.410
Against too much presentism.

00:23:34.410 --> 00:23:37.130
You know, there are things
unique about our era.

00:23:37.130 --> 00:23:39.760
But in some ways,
they're, you know,

00:23:39.760 --> 00:23:41.750
other leaders have faced
the same kind of problems.

00:23:41.750 --> 00:23:45.020
And here's Kennedy
writing about them in 1956.

00:23:45.020 --> 00:23:49.010
Without social media, without
the internet in a different age.

00:23:49.010 --> 00:23:52.290
So it has changed
it, but to be honest

00:23:52.290 --> 00:23:53.590
with you, I say in the book.

00:23:53.590 --> 00:23:57.340
You know, we've seen the
emergence, for better or worse.

00:23:57.340 --> 00:23:59.710
Of very powerful,
strong leaders, you know?

00:23:59.710 --> 00:24:02.410
I mean, saying this as
a purely analytic point,

00:24:02.410 --> 00:24:03.710
but there's no question

00:24:03.710 --> 00:24:06.470
that President Donald Trump
has demonstrated the impact an

00:24:06.470 --> 00:24:08.900
individual can have in the
position of the Presidency.

00:24:08.900 --> 00:24:11.110
So the notion that
the Presidency can't

00:24:11.110 --> 00:24:12.410
provide leadership.

00:24:12.410 --> 00:24:15.440
Putin and others and
maybe I'm giving examples

00:24:15.440 --> 00:24:17.280
that maybe aren't on
the constructive side.

00:24:17.280 --> 00:24:21.350
But I think that you
know that it shows

00:24:21.350 --> 00:24:23.420
that leadership is possible.

00:24:23.420 --> 00:24:26.490
Even in this environment
and you know there's a lot

00:24:26.490 --> 00:24:27.790
of bottom-up that happens.

00:24:27.790 --> 00:24:29.230
The Arab Spring was bottom-up.

00:24:29.230 --> 00:24:30.960
There's a lot of
middle-out that happens

00:24:30.960 --> 00:24:33.130
from science, technology.

00:24:33.130 --> 00:24:36.290
There's some work here where I
draw on the business literature.

00:24:36.290 --> 00:24:38.630
And the challenges
of transformation

00:24:38.630 --> 00:24:39.930
in the business community

00:24:39.930 --> 00:24:42.400
or the higher-ed community
are in some ways similar.

00:24:42.400 --> 00:24:45.310
But I, I don't think that,
that, I think you have

00:24:45.310 --> 00:24:48.250
to you know take into account
certain characteristics

00:24:48.250 --> 00:24:51.590
of today's political and
communications environment.

00:24:51.590 --> 00:24:54.100
But we still, it's not
totally unique compare,

00:24:54.100 --> 00:24:55.410
compared to others.

00:24:55.410 --> 00:24:56.840
&gt;&gt; John Haskell:
Of course people by

00:24:56.840 --> 00:24:58.370
and large haven't
had an opportunity

00:24:58.370 --> 00:24:59.670
to read the book yet.

00:24:59.670 --> 00:25:02.270
Here and lest anybody
get the impression it's,

00:25:02.270 --> 00:25:05.430
that you're doing a
great-man theory of history.

00:25:05.430 --> 00:25:08.500
There, there are chapters in
there about social movements,

00:25:08.500 --> 00:25:09.800
NGOs, that kind of thing.

00:25:09.800 --> 00:25:13.010
Do you have, do you want to
say a word, too, about those?

00:25:13.010 --> 00:25:15.270
&gt;&gt; Dr. Bruce Jentleson: Sure,
so two, three of the chapters

00:25:15.270 --> 00:25:18.160
that relate to that, I'll
make mention here briefly.

00:25:18.160 --> 00:25:23.610
One is on Northern Ireland,
and two Northern Irish women:

00:25:23.610 --> 00:25:25.350
Betty Williams and
Mairead Corrigan.

00:25:25.350 --> 00:25:28.510
Who are everyday folks.

00:25:28.510 --> 00:25:32.990
And the story starts in
19-- so from 1969 on,

00:25:32.990 --> 00:25:36.310
what's called The Troubles,
the level of violence

00:25:36.310 --> 00:25:38.920
and killing was rapidly
going up.

00:25:38.920 --> 00:25:45.910
And in 1972, Mairead
Corrigan's sister was walking

00:25:45.910 --> 00:25:49.200
down the street in
Belfast with three

00:25:49.200 --> 00:25:51.160
of her, four of her children.

00:25:51.160 --> 00:25:56.190
And an IRA getaway car, driver
lost control, smashed into them.

00:25:56.190 --> 00:26:00.080
Injured her seriously, and
killed a couple of the children.

00:26:00.080 --> 00:26:03.930
And it was being chased
by a British police car.

00:26:03.930 --> 00:26:06.080
And so Mairead Corrigan
who was a secretary

00:26:06.080 --> 00:26:09.920
in a Guinness brewery
goes to the hospital.

00:26:09.920 --> 00:26:12.900
And this actually relates to
your, to your previous question.

00:26:12.900 --> 00:26:15.570
And comes out, and the BBC
reporters are all out there.

00:26:15.570 --> 00:26:17.780
And she makes a statement
along the lines of--

00:26:17.780 --> 00:26:19.080
I have the exact
quote in the book.

00:26:19.080 --> 00:26:22.100
Of you know, in only less than
five percent of the people

00:26:22.100 --> 00:26:23.930
in Northern Ireland really
want these things to happen.

00:26:23.930 --> 00:26:25.420
The rest of us are tired of it.

00:26:25.420 --> 00:26:26.860
And as we would say
today, it went viral.

00:26:26.860 --> 00:26:28.850
It went all over BBC.

00:26:28.850 --> 00:26:30.640
It went all over the world.

00:26:30.640 --> 00:26:34.010
It was a person and moment.

00:26:34.010 --> 00:26:35.420
Betty Williams, you know,

00:26:35.420 --> 00:26:37.910
it was another person
in, in Northern Ireland.

00:26:37.910 --> 00:26:39.210
They come together,

00:26:39.210 --> 00:26:41.980
they organize the Northern
Ireland Women for Peace.

00:26:41.980 --> 00:26:44.620
And they bring in some
political organizers.

00:26:44.620 --> 00:26:48.210
And the level of violence
never goes up to that level.

00:26:48.210 --> 00:26:51.830
It takes another 20-plus years
and our friend, George Mitchell.

00:26:51.830 --> 00:26:56.070
And the, the, the you know,
and the negotiator skills

00:26:56.070 --> 00:26:58.430
to bring the Good
Friday Agreement around.

00:26:58.430 --> 00:27:00.650
And in fact Betty Williams and,

00:27:00.650 --> 00:27:02.290
and Mairead Corrigan win the
Nobel Peace Prize I think

00:27:02.290 --> 00:27:04.860
in '76 or '77.

00:27:04.860 --> 00:27:07.370
And they reached the limit
of their political skills.

00:27:07.370 --> 00:27:08.720
They kind of get pushed aside.

00:27:08.720 --> 00:27:10.710
There are a couple small
scandals that get pushed aside.

00:27:10.710 --> 00:27:12.010
And others take it over.

00:27:12.010 --> 00:27:13.530
But, but they were
transformational

00:27:13.530 --> 00:27:14.830
for that moment.

00:27:14.830 --> 00:27:16.540
You know, there are
all these marches all

00:27:16.540 --> 00:27:17.840
over Northern Ireland.

00:27:17.840 --> 00:27:19.140
It really changed the dynamics.

00:27:19.140 --> 00:27:21.560
I was in grad school in
London at the, at that time.

00:27:21.560 --> 00:27:24.240
There were bombings in Harrod's
and other sorts of things.

00:27:24.240 --> 00:27:27.520
So that's one of the stories
that shows how, you know,

00:27:27.520 --> 00:27:28.900
civil society, if you will.

00:27:28.900 --> 00:27:30.520
Can, can, can transform
the moment.

00:27:30.520 --> 00:27:32.510
Again, can't make
the peace agreement.

00:27:32.510 --> 00:27:34.340
And whatever else is happening
in Northern Ireland today.

00:27:34.340 --> 00:27:37.070
It's hardly total peace,
but it has not gone back

00:27:37.070 --> 00:27:38.870
to the violence that it was.

00:27:38.870 --> 00:27:41.490
Second story is about
the rise of the,

00:27:41.490 --> 00:27:43.190
of the contemporary
human rights movement.

00:27:43.190 --> 00:27:46.850
And I start it with, and
it's again, contemporary.

00:27:46.850 --> 00:27:48.290
It goes back many centuries.

00:27:48.290 --> 00:27:51.730
In 1961, a British lawyer by
the name of Peter Benenson

00:27:51.730 --> 00:27:54.570
who was sort of an odd duck.

00:27:54.570 --> 00:27:58.260
Had run for the House of
Commons three times and lost.

00:27:58.260 --> 00:28:01.520
But had been involved actually
through his mother and others

00:28:01.520 --> 00:28:05.240
in protecting children
in the '30s and '40s.

00:28:05.240 --> 00:28:08.300
Not only from Hitler, but
from Franco and Salazar

00:28:08.300 --> 00:28:09.600
in Spain and Portugal.

00:28:09.600 --> 00:28:11.390
And so he begins to think

00:28:11.390 --> 00:28:13.000
about what he calls
prisoners of conscience.

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:16.650
And he writes an op-ed in
The Observer of London.

00:28:16.650 --> 00:28:17.950
And again, it goes viral.

00:28:17.950 --> 00:28:20.190
I mean, you know, I've written
a lot of op-eds in my life.

00:28:20.190 --> 00:28:21.490
And you always hope
they go viral.

00:28:21.490 --> 00:28:23.830
You know, you know,
maybe a few Twitter,

00:28:23.830 --> 00:28:25.590
Twitterings, but not a lot.

00:28:25.590 --> 00:28:28.480
And, and it's picked up by
newspapers all over the world.

00:28:28.480 --> 00:28:29.780
And it's this new concept

00:28:29.780 --> 00:28:32.810
for a grassroots human
rights organization.

00:28:32.810 --> 00:28:35.910
Within three years, you know,
donations are coming in.

00:28:35.910 --> 00:28:37.950
And you know, the
number of chapters

00:28:37.950 --> 00:28:41.010
of Amnesty International
increases exponentially.

00:28:41.010 --> 00:28:45.200
By 1967, he's actually kicked
out of the organization.

00:28:45.200 --> 00:28:47.960
And political skills took
him to a certain point.

00:28:47.960 --> 00:28:49.440
And others take it
over, and it grows

00:28:49.440 --> 00:28:51.420
as we know Amnesty
International today.

00:28:51.420 --> 00:28:55.360
But, but, but it really seeds
the human rights movement.

00:28:55.360 --> 00:28:59.000
Human Rights Watch, you know,
all these groups we know today.

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:01.550
That in many ways you could
argue are more prominent.

00:29:01.550 --> 00:29:04.230
But they really kicked
it off, and,

00:29:04.230 --> 00:29:06.480
and they do in many respects,

00:29:06.480 --> 00:29:09.580
what governments are
unable or unwilling to do.

00:29:09.580 --> 00:29:12.300
And so that's one of the
other stories that, again,

00:29:12.300 --> 00:29:13.600
you know, non-obvious.

00:29:13.600 --> 00:29:15.400
He wasn't somebody
that you saw coming.

00:29:15.400 --> 00:29:19.490
And the third one is about the
Gates Foundation and its work

00:29:19.490 --> 00:29:21.220
in global public health.

00:29:21.220 --> 00:29:22.600
And what I call the rise

00:29:22.600 --> 00:29:25.220
of philanthropy statesmanship,
you know?

00:29:25.220 --> 00:29:28.120
The Gates Foundation is
the second-largest budget

00:29:28.120 --> 00:29:29.730
in the world today for
global public health,

00:29:29.730 --> 00:29:31.720
next to World Health
Organization.

00:29:31.720 --> 00:29:33.510
And what they have
done in that sector.

00:29:33.510 --> 00:29:35.340
And it's not, I mean,
there are criticisms

00:29:35.340 --> 00:29:38.380
of the Gates Foundation
and I address those just

00:29:38.380 --> 00:29:39.790
like with [inaudible] Kissinger.

00:29:39.790 --> 00:29:41.350
But I do believe I'm balanced

00:29:41.350 --> 00:29:43.060
that they've made an
enormous difference there.

00:29:43.060 --> 00:29:47.530
And that they exemplify
this emergence

00:29:47.530 --> 00:29:48.930
of philanthropy statesmanship.

00:29:48.930 --> 00:29:51.860
The role of philanthropies,
you know, Bill Gates

00:29:51.860 --> 00:29:54.360
and Warren Budget, Buffett
now have this giving pledge

00:29:54.360 --> 00:29:55.660
where they're getting.

00:29:55.660 --> 00:29:57.660
You know, very wealthy people
around the world to commit

00:29:57.660 --> 00:30:00.550
to not just foundations that
spend at their five percent.

00:30:00.550 --> 00:30:03.480
But to give away 50% of their
wealth in their lifetime.

00:30:03.480 --> 00:30:06.270
So those are three examples
that complement, you know,

00:30:06.270 --> 00:30:11.480
the Kissingers, the Rabins,
the Mandelas that I think are,

00:30:11.480 --> 00:30:13.210
really are statesmanship
in their own way.

00:30:13.210 --> 00:30:16.430
And again, in the 21st
century I think are trendlines

00:30:16.430 --> 00:30:17.730
that are going on.

00:30:17.730 --> 00:30:19.110
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: Let's
talk about the 21st century

00:30:19.110 --> 00:30:22.190
and sort of draw some lessons.

00:30:22.190 --> 00:30:23.890
Because you know
your peacemakers,

00:30:23.890 --> 00:30:25.190
among many other things,

00:30:25.190 --> 00:30:26.980
contributed to the
end of the Cold War.

00:30:26.980 --> 00:30:31.090
But things aren't great
right now, some would argue,

00:30:31.090 --> 00:30:32.940
between the U.S. and Russia.

00:30:32.940 --> 00:30:36.270
And what kind of
lessons do you draw from,

00:30:36.270 --> 00:30:37.570
in the book about that?

00:30:37.570 --> 00:30:38.870
&gt;&gt; Dr. Bruce Jentleson: Yeah,
I've been really pushing back

00:30:38.870 --> 00:30:40.690
against people calling
this "new cold war" stuff.

00:30:40.690 --> 00:30:42.210
You know, it's an
easy little one-liner.

00:30:42.210 --> 00:30:46.110
But if you think about
it, it's not global.

00:30:46.110 --> 00:30:48.300
It's not ideological.

00:30:48.300 --> 00:30:51.110
And we're not on the
brink of nuclear war.

00:30:51.110 --> 00:30:53.130
As I look around the room,
those of us who lived

00:30:53.130 --> 00:30:57.290
through the Cuban Missile Crisis
can remember that all too well.

00:30:57.290 --> 00:31:01.830
It's classic major power
you know competition.

00:31:01.830 --> 00:31:03.810
U.S.-China has an
element of that.

00:31:03.810 --> 00:31:06.690
The case I've actually been,
been in the process of trying

00:31:06.690 --> 00:31:09.120
to write something to
make, make the linkage on.

00:31:09.120 --> 00:31:11.920
Is looking at the summitry
from those and how it relates

00:31:11.920 --> 00:31:14.430
to the U.S. perspective.

00:31:14.430 --> 00:31:16.290
U.S.-North Korea summit.

00:31:16.290 --> 00:31:18.430
And the pattern that I trace

00:31:18.430 --> 00:31:21.400
in both the Gorbachev
chapter and Reagan.

00:31:21.400 --> 00:31:22.770
I, I give more credit to Reagan

00:31:22.770 --> 00:31:24.760
than probably some
other academics do.

00:31:24.760 --> 00:31:27.120
Maybe less than some people that
are on the conservative side.

00:31:27.120 --> 00:31:28.420
But he was a crucial partner.

00:31:28.420 --> 00:31:30.660
My argument is really
Gorbachev was the absolutely

00:31:30.660 --> 00:31:31.960
indispensable one.

00:31:31.960 --> 00:31:35.960
And the Kissinger is, there
were three elements that make

00:31:35.960 --> 00:31:37.260
for successful summitry.

00:31:37.260 --> 00:31:39.420
And this could apply to
U.S.-Russian, U.S.-China.

00:31:39.420 --> 00:31:41.910
But I think you know North
Korea's on our mind a lot.

00:31:41.910 --> 00:31:45.960
And I, you know, I guess I do
alliteration on my three C's.

00:31:45.960 --> 00:31:47.690
This is the three P's.

00:31:47.690 --> 00:31:49.310
It's the personal, the
policy, and the political.

00:31:49.310 --> 00:31:51.660
That, that in the
cases we looked at.

00:31:51.660 --> 00:31:54.460
As I talked about
with the handshake,

00:31:54.460 --> 00:31:55.800
personal trust was developed.

00:31:55.800 --> 00:31:57.630
Reagan and Gorbachev
developed an enormous amount

00:31:57.630 --> 00:31:58.930
of political trust.

00:31:58.930 --> 00:32:00.230
Actually to the consternation
of some

00:32:00.230 --> 00:32:02.160
of Reagan's hawkish advisors.

00:32:02.160 --> 00:32:06.310
That makes possible
concessions and the belief

00:32:06.310 --> 00:32:08.800
that your partner is
being straight with you

00:32:08.800 --> 00:32:11.060
and will lead to other things.

00:32:11.060 --> 00:32:13.170
Policy which is based
on a mutuality.

00:32:13.170 --> 00:32:15.600
Just like I said about
Taiwan and Vietnam.

00:32:15.600 --> 00:32:17.010
We each got some.

00:32:17.010 --> 00:32:18.310
You know, that there's
a mutuality

00:32:18.310 --> 00:32:20.370
and not one side
thinking they're coming

00:32:20.370 --> 00:32:21.670
out with everything.

00:32:21.670 --> 00:32:24.430
And then the politics which is
managing with constituencies.

00:32:24.430 --> 00:32:27.120
If we look at, and every day we
hear whether the summit's going

00:32:27.120 --> 00:32:28.420
to happen or not.

00:32:28.420 --> 00:32:30.430
But let's just assume it does.

00:32:30.430 --> 00:32:33.850
You know, I actually think the
politics is my least worry.

00:32:33.850 --> 00:32:37.780
You know, the whole Nixon
goes to China, you know.

00:32:37.780 --> 00:32:41.190
Conceivably, Trump could
manage the politics of backlash

00:32:41.190 --> 00:32:43.030
about a deal with North Korea.

00:32:43.030 --> 00:32:47.830
And, and presumably Kim
Jong Un can do it at home.

00:32:47.830 --> 00:32:50.570
The policy I worry
about a lot you know.

00:32:50.570 --> 00:32:52.110
I don't see a lot
of mutuality there.

00:32:52.110 --> 00:32:55.880
It would have to be
you know, policy change

00:32:55.880 --> 00:32:57.180
and that regime change.

00:32:57.180 --> 00:32:58.930
North Koreans are interested
and part of their motivation

00:32:58.930 --> 00:33:01.140
for nuclear weapons
is an insurance policy

00:33:01.140 --> 00:33:02.670
against regime change.

00:33:02.670 --> 00:33:05.670
They look at what Libya
gave up in the early 2000s.

00:33:05.670 --> 00:33:07.540
They look at what Saddam
got taken away by the UN.

00:33:07.540 --> 00:33:10.660
And, and I think there really
has to be a lot of mutuality

00:33:10.660 --> 00:33:11.960
and reciprocity in there.

00:33:11.960 --> 00:33:14.690
I'm not optimistic about the
way that pre [inaudible].

00:33:14.690 --> 00:33:16.380
And then the personal.

00:33:16.380 --> 00:33:17.680
And again, I'll be honest.

00:33:17.680 --> 00:33:23.020
I'm not sure either of these
leaders has any experience

00:33:23.020 --> 00:33:25.450
or the temperament that's
conducive to the kind

00:33:25.450 --> 00:33:28.520
of relationships and
trust-building that we saw

00:33:28.520 --> 00:33:29.820
in the other, other two cases.

00:33:29.820 --> 00:33:32.870
So I feel like there's a
little bit of a formula there.

00:33:32.870 --> 00:33:35.490
Personal policy and politics
for successful summitry.

00:33:35.490 --> 00:33:38.660
