00:36:02.430 --> 00:36:03.730
&gt;&gt; Dr. Bruce Jentleson:
So [inaudible] I titled

00:36:03.730 --> 00:36:06.050
that chapter "Hammarskjold
the Secular Pope."

00:36:06.050 --> 00:36:09.630
When he came in, he was seen as
a nameless, faceless bureaucrat.

00:36:09.630 --> 00:36:13.010
Who, but and his predecessor,

00:36:13.010 --> 00:36:15.470
the first Secretary-General
described the job

00:36:15.470 --> 00:36:17.780
as the most impossible
in the world.

00:36:17.780 --> 00:36:22.540
Hammarskjold had a
huge impact on a number

00:36:22.540 --> 00:36:25.980
of issues before he died
in a plane crash that's,

00:36:25.980 --> 00:36:28.090
once again, being investigated.

00:36:28.090 --> 00:36:30.240
And let me just tell one of
the stories because it relates

00:36:30.240 --> 00:36:31.540
to today particularly.

00:36:31.540 --> 00:36:34.090
In 1956 and the Suez Crisis.

00:36:34.090 --> 00:36:37.940
When Britain and France
and Israel invaded Egypt

00:36:37.940 --> 00:36:40.270
because of Gamal Abdel
Nasser's nationalization

00:36:40.270 --> 00:36:41.570
of the Suez Canal.

00:36:41.570 --> 00:36:43.250
So you had two permanent members

00:36:43.250 --> 00:36:47.190
of the Security Council
invading another country.

00:36:47.190 --> 00:36:49.160
And you had the United States
and the Soviet Union looking

00:36:49.160 --> 00:36:50.760
at it from a Cold
War perspective.

00:36:50.760 --> 00:36:52.920
And so you had the
coming together

00:36:52.920 --> 00:36:56.030
in this crisis anti-colonialism.

00:36:56.030 --> 00:37:02.310
The Cold War, the Middle
East, all of these issues.

00:37:02.310 --> 00:37:05.710
And Hammarskjold was the
one with some assistance

00:37:05.710 --> 00:37:08.510
from the Canadian Ambassador,
Lester Mike Pearson,

00:37:08.510 --> 00:37:10.560
who managed the crisis.

00:37:10.560 --> 00:37:12.700
He went in and did
the diplomacy.

00:37:12.700 --> 00:37:16.600
Got the British and the French
and the Israelis to withdraw.

00:37:16.600 --> 00:37:18.240
He-- .

00:37:18.240 --> 00:37:21.780
Went in and negotiated
with Nasser.

00:37:21.780 --> 00:37:24.640
He and Pearson formed the
first major United Nations

00:37:24.640 --> 00:37:26.030
peace-keeping force.

00:37:26.030 --> 00:37:29.460
That went into Suez
that was successful.

00:37:29.460 --> 00:37:31.770
And he did everything that,
that, you know, both the,

00:37:31.770 --> 00:37:33.590
the strategy and the
ideas to the practical.

00:37:33.590 --> 00:37:36.230
Oh my god, we've got to deploy
these countries' peace-keepers

00:37:36.230 --> 00:37:37.530
right away.

00:37:37.530 --> 00:37:40.600
But we don't have helmets.

00:37:40.600 --> 00:37:42.900
So they took some
American surplus helmets

00:37:42.900 --> 00:37:44.200
and they painted them blue.

00:37:44.200 --> 00:37:45.550
You know, that's
the blue helmets.

00:37:45.550 --> 00:37:48.310
So he, he really
resolved the crisis.

00:37:48.310 --> 00:37:51.740
And so in the latest
you know couple weeks,

00:37:51.740 --> 00:37:54.270
month or so ago,
a little more now.

00:37:54.270 --> 00:37:55.570
Crisis in Syria.

00:37:55.570 --> 00:37:58.990
It's always been a crisis, but
the U.S.-Russia confrontation.

00:37:58.990 --> 00:38:01.470
I was talking to some reporters.

00:38:01.470 --> 00:38:03.080
I said, you know, you know,

00:38:03.080 --> 00:38:06.020
we need to empower the
Secretary-General the way

00:38:06.020 --> 00:38:07.820
that Hammarskjold was empowered.

00:38:07.820 --> 00:38:09.830
And it may not be the
first-choice strategy

00:38:09.830 --> 00:38:11.270
for either the United
States or Russia.

00:38:11.270 --> 00:38:14.370
But it's probably a pretty
good second-choice strategy.

00:38:14.370 --> 00:38:16.590
And there is a UN negotiator,
but he's not empowered.

00:38:16.590 --> 00:38:18.850
I was actually involved in
this very issue when I was

00:38:18.850 --> 00:38:20.370
in the Obama Administration.

00:38:20.370 --> 00:38:23.540
And, and, and, and
said look, you know,

00:38:23.540 --> 00:38:24.920
all the major powers
say oh my god,

00:38:24.920 --> 00:38:27.460
we can't have a powerful
Secretary-General.

00:38:27.460 --> 00:38:29.800
You know, you have to
give up some prerogative.

00:38:29.800 --> 00:38:33.120
Right? All, China would, Russia
would, the United States.

00:38:33.120 --> 00:38:34.520
But no Secretary-General's
ever going

00:38:34.520 --> 00:38:36.440
to tell the major
powers what to do

00:38:36.440 --> 00:38:37.990
on an issue that's
absolutely crucial

00:38:37.990 --> 00:38:39.590
to their vital interests.

00:38:39.590 --> 00:38:41.530
But what you gain for
the prerogative you give

00:38:41.530 --> 00:38:44.490
up is you know a
better strategy.

00:38:44.490 --> 00:38:47.800
For, for, for crises that
affect your own interests.

00:38:47.800 --> 00:38:49.960
And so you're making
that gain there.

00:38:49.960 --> 00:38:51.260
And so there's an
argument in the book

00:38:51.260 --> 00:38:52.680
about why we need
a Hammarskjold-ian

00:38:52.680 --> 00:38:53.980
Secretary-General.

00:38:53.980 --> 00:38:56.080
It's not so much a direct
criticism [inaudible].

00:38:56.080 --> 00:38:59.270
It's really more you know
how the job is defined.

00:38:59.270 --> 00:39:01.610
And until then, and the UN
has a lot of other problems.

00:39:01.610 --> 00:39:02.910
This wouldn't solve them all.

00:39:02.910 --> 00:39:05.520
But what organization do we
know, whether it's a government

00:39:05.520 --> 00:39:08.260
or large organization that
can deal with its problems

00:39:08.260 --> 00:39:10.710
if it doesn't have
a CEO, in effect?

00:39:10.710 --> 00:39:12.900
Who people respect
and is powerful?

00:39:12.900 --> 00:39:15.590
And so I really think
that that's crucial.

00:39:15.590 --> 00:39:17.700
If we want the UN
to be effective,

00:39:17.700 --> 00:39:19.630
we really need a more
empowered Secretary-General.

00:39:19.630 --> 00:39:21.850
And I kind of take on
the political arguments

00:39:21.850 --> 00:39:23.150
and push back against them.

00:39:23.150 --> 00:39:25.060
Why, why this is
actually in our interest.

00:39:25.060 --> 00:39:26.450
It's not a concession.

