00:42:48.150 --> 00:42:50.300
&gt;&gt; Audience Question: Yeah, you
were talking about the, the,

00:42:50.300 --> 00:42:51.600
the effectiveness of the UN.

00:42:51.600 --> 00:42:55.380
And I was wondering, do
you think the legitimacy

00:42:55.380 --> 00:42:59.580
of the UN's moral like authority
has been hampered recently?

00:42:59.580 --> 00:43:01.580
Especially like I'll give an
example off the top of my head.

00:43:01.580 --> 00:43:05.010
The Human Rights Council
having countries like Russia

00:43:05.010 --> 00:43:07.250
and Venezuela on their board.

00:43:07.250 --> 00:43:10.170
Do you think that hampers
the effectiveness of the UN?

00:43:10.170 --> 00:43:11.760
&gt;&gt; Dr. Bruce Jentleson:
Unquestionably it does.

00:43:11.760 --> 00:43:13.270
That's what I said,
there are many issues.

00:43:13.270 --> 00:43:16.280
There's just a commission
chaired by Kevin Rudd,

00:43:16.280 --> 00:43:18.720
former Australian Prime Minister

00:43:18.720 --> 00:43:23.380
that has a long agenda
for UN reform.

00:43:23.380 --> 00:43:24.840
That's one.

00:43:24.840 --> 00:43:26.560
There have been scandals
with peace-keepers.

00:43:26.560 --> 00:43:28.610
You know, sexual scandals
with peace-keepers.

00:43:28.610 --> 00:43:31.820
You know, I guess there's
bringing cholera to Haiti.

00:43:31.820 --> 00:43:33.300
There are a whole
slew of issues.

00:43:33.300 --> 00:43:36.400
My sense of things though is,

00:43:36.400 --> 00:43:40.720
is you know we need an effective
UN in the world, right?

00:43:40.720 --> 00:43:44.910
And, and we need it
frankly now more than ever.

00:43:44.910 --> 00:43:47.110
And so.

00:43:47.110 --> 00:43:50.030
You know, you know,
the only thing I deal

00:43:50.030 --> 00:43:52.690
with in this book is, is the
role of Secretary-General.

00:43:52.690 --> 00:43:53.990
Because I think a lot
of things should flow,

00:43:53.990 --> 00:43:55.290
could flow from that.

00:43:55.290 --> 00:43:57.070
Hammarskjold's notion
of the Secular Pope was

00:43:57.070 --> 00:43:59.400
about the moral authority
that, you know,

00:43:59.400 --> 00:44:02.100
that he exercised
and brought it there.

00:44:02.100 --> 00:44:05.230
There are things that UN can
do that governments can't do.

00:44:05.230 --> 00:44:07.500
I mean, Syria's, to me is a
really good example right now.

00:44:07.500 --> 00:44:09.170
And there are a whole
host of others.

00:44:09.170 --> 00:44:12.000
And many other reforms are
going to have to happen.

00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:13.720
But sometimes we look at the UN.

00:44:13.720 --> 00:44:16.220
And we say, "Here's
all its negatives."

00:44:16.220 --> 00:44:18.640
And we look we look at American
foreign policy, and we say,

00:44:18.640 --> 00:44:19.940
"Here's all its positives."

00:44:19.940 --> 00:44:23.230
And so we've got to do a
two-column accounting of both.

00:44:23.230 --> 00:44:24.530
And then figure out
how to change it.

00:44:24.530 --> 00:44:26.200
Because we really do
need an effective UN.

00:44:26.200 --> 00:44:29.200
And you know the
notion of blowing it up

00:44:29.200 --> 00:44:31.920
or cutting off our funding.

00:44:31.920 --> 00:44:34.650
Or telling countries that
don't vote the way we want them

00:44:34.650 --> 00:44:36.530
to that we're not going to,
we're not going to give them,

00:44:36.530 --> 00:44:38.030
you know, foreign aid.

00:44:38.030 --> 00:44:39.620
It's just counterproductive,
right?

00:44:39.620 --> 00:44:42.430
So you know, it's been a
little bit of tough love among,

00:44:42.430 --> 00:44:44.280
directed at kind of
liberal internationalists,

00:44:44.280 --> 00:44:45.580
people that do believe
in the UN.

00:44:45.580 --> 00:44:47.950
It's not enough to say what's
wrong with the anti-UN.

00:44:47.950 --> 00:44:50.440
You know, if you really
believe in the UN,

00:44:50.440 --> 00:44:52.060
you've got to do a
little tough love on it.

00:44:52.060 --> 00:44:55.350
And part of what I'm doing in
this book is along those lines.

