you can derive from this

00:47:52.630 --> 00:47:54.080
in each of those five areas.

00:47:54.080 --> 00:47:56.610
And there's similarities
and differences for it.

00:47:56.610 --> 00:47:59.660
I actually have a chapter I
was working on, on the founding

00:47:59.660 --> 00:48:03.130
of the EU but we have to again,

00:48:03.130 --> 00:48:05.900
make it you know,
marketing a book.

00:48:05.900 --> 00:48:07.780
You know, you have to, we
have to keep the length.

00:48:07.780 --> 00:48:09.560
And it was going to be
about Monnet, Schuman,

00:48:09.560 --> 00:48:11.810
and Adenauer together in
the founding of the EU

00:48:11.810 --> 00:48:14.180
because you know, whatever
else the EU's done wrong,

00:48:14.180 --> 00:48:17.650
the fact that you know there
has not been a major power war

00:48:17.650 --> 00:48:20.270
in Europe after two world
wars start there is not,

00:48:20.270 --> 00:48:21.570
not small potatoes.

00:48:21.570 --> 00:48:25.000
So I think its challenges
are, are, are policy.

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:28.260
My own analysis is
they, you know,

00:48:28.260 --> 00:48:33.040
they didn't keep symmetrical
the political change

00:48:33.040 --> 00:48:34.910
and the policy and
economic change.

00:48:34.910 --> 00:48:36.380
So they had this
enormous integration.

00:48:36.380 --> 00:48:38.440
They went to a single currency.

00:48:38.440 --> 00:48:40.870
There was a rule that you
couldn't run about more

00:48:40.870 --> 00:48:45.250
than 2.7, two percent of your
GDP as your fiscal deficit.

00:48:45.250 --> 00:48:47.280
Nobody enforced it, you know.

00:48:47.280 --> 00:48:49.850
So Greece ran up its deficit.

00:48:49.850 --> 00:48:51.660
And Germany then came
in which really had all

00:48:51.660 --> 00:48:52.960
of the economic power

00:48:52.960 --> 00:48:55.160
and imposed its own,
you know, views.

00:48:55.160 --> 00:48:56.460
Which were coming
out of what it went

00:48:56.460 --> 00:48:57.760
through in the [inaudible]
Republic.

00:48:57.760 --> 00:49:00.480
So they're going to have to
find a greater, you know,

00:49:00.480 --> 00:49:02.360
kind of equilibrium
between how far they want

00:49:02.360 --> 00:49:03.660
to take the political change.

00:49:03.660 --> 00:49:05.830
And how much they
coordinate policy.

00:49:05.830 --> 00:49:08.990
I think they've actually
seen the worst of their days.

00:49:08.990 --> 00:49:11.010
I just came back from Britain.

00:49:11.010 --> 00:49:16.480
And in June 2016, I had been
invited to London, to the,

00:49:16.480 --> 00:49:18.340
to Chatham House [inaudible]
International Affairs

00:49:18.340 --> 00:49:21.680
to give a talk on how our
domestic policy was affecting

00:49:21.680 --> 00:49:22.980
our foreign policy.

00:49:22.980 --> 00:49:24.750
Turned out to be three
days after Brexit.

00:49:24.750 --> 00:49:28.950
So I walked and said, "Why don't
you guys talk to me, you know?"

00:49:28.950 --> 00:49:31.060
And so Brexit is a huge issue.

00:49:31.060 --> 00:49:33.480
You know, Catalonia
may be an issue.

00:49:33.480 --> 00:49:36.890
The right wing is a huge issue.

00:49:36.890 --> 00:49:40.480
But I, I think that they're
going to have to manage those.

00:49:40.480 --> 00:49:44.070
You know, my own sense is, is
I think the EU can survive it.

00:49:44.070 --> 00:49:46.770
But at the same time, in the
nuts and bolts of policy.

00:49:46.770 --> 00:49:50.710
It's going to have to figure
out, you know, how to, you know,

00:49:50.710 --> 00:49:52.960
you know, if its wants
more political integration.

00:49:52.960 --> 00:49:55.250
It's going to have
to you know impose,

00:49:55.250 --> 00:49:57.180
make the governments comply.

00:49:57.180 --> 00:49:58.800
Because it's still kind of
like the United Nations.

00:49:58.800 --> 00:50:00.100
It's really a bunch

00:50:00.100 --> 00:50:02.240
of governments coming
together under an umbrella.

00:50:02.240 --> 00:50:03.540
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: We
got, yeah, Andrew?

00:50:03.540 --> 00:50:04.840
&gt;&gt; Audience Question:
Thank you very much

00:50:04.840 --> 00:50:07.150
for a most interesting
discussion.

00:50:07.150 --> 00:50:09.940
I would appreciate your
inclusion of social movements

00:50:09.940 --> 00:50:11.970
and non-governmental
organizations.

00:50:11.970 --> 00:50:14.680
And I also appreciate
the fact that you point

00:50:14.680 --> 00:50:16.390
out that there are
limitations to what they can do.

00:50:16.390 --> 00:50:18.980
And eventually state
institutions

00:50:18.980 --> 00:50:21.150
and governmental
authorities have to pick up.

00:50:21.150 --> 00:50:23.340
In order to push
the process along.

00:50:23.340 --> 00:50:25.390
You think about Martin
Luther King,

00:50:25.390 --> 00:50:26.690
pushing up from the bottom.

00:50:26.690 --> 00:50:28.260
And Lyndon Johnson
pushing down from the top

00:50:28.260 --> 00:50:29.990
to achieve Civil
Rights legislation.

00:50:29.990 --> 00:50:32.380
I'm wondering, based on
your historical research,

00:50:32.380 --> 00:50:34.590
can you offer suggestions

00:50:34.590 --> 00:50:36.800
for that process of
passing the baton?

00:50:36.800 --> 00:50:39.450
From social movement to
government institutions?

00:50:39.450 --> 00:50:41.020
How do we ease that along?

00:50:41.020 --> 00:50:42.320
&gt;&gt; Dr. Bruce Jentleson:
Let me give you an example.

00:50:42.320 --> 00:50:44.020
In the, in the section on
your know advancing freedom

00:50:44.020 --> 00:50:45.880
and human rights that
the Amnesty International

00:50:45.880 --> 00:50:47.180
chapter's in.

00:50:47.180 --> 00:50:48.480
And some of the others.

00:50:48.480 --> 00:50:51.580
At the end I say that
you know, NGOs are going

00:50:51.580 --> 00:50:56.290
to be extremely important
in the human rights area.

00:50:56.290 --> 00:50:58.890
Because the reality, whether
it's the Human Rights Council

00:50:58.890 --> 00:51:00.250
or US foreign policy.

00:51:00.250 --> 00:51:04.050
There's a lot of inconsistency,
to say the least there.

00:51:04.050 --> 00:51:08.170
And so what we're seeing
as, as NGOs, you know,

00:51:08.170 --> 00:51:09.750
get the kind of technologies.

00:51:09.750 --> 00:51:11.650
So for example with what
was happening with Rohingya,

00:51:11.650 --> 00:51:13.980
the first reports came
from Human Rights Watch.

00:51:13.980 --> 00:51:16.440
Who now had satellite technology
they could photograph.

00:51:16.440 --> 00:51:19.060
The same way we were dependent
upon intelligence agencies

00:51:19.060 --> 00:51:20.360
to do.

00:51:20.360 --> 00:51:21.660
And intelligence agencies
of governments may

00:51:21.660 --> 00:51:23.450
or may not share
that information.

00:51:23.450 --> 00:51:25.360
So I actually think
they will continue

00:51:25.360 --> 00:51:30.220
to be extremely important on
flagging human rights issues.

00:51:30.220 --> 00:51:32.550
They've developed enormous
expertise over the years.

00:51:32.550 --> 00:51:35.360
There's little market
competition among human right--

00:51:35.360 --> 00:51:37.350
human rights NGOs because
they all need funding

00:51:37.350 --> 00:51:39.290
from foundations and others.

00:51:39.290 --> 00:51:40.590
But you're right.

00:51:40.590 --> 00:51:43.290
At the end of the day, they
can't change the policy, right?

00:51:43.290 --> 00:51:44.910
So I think that you know

00:51:44.910 --> 00:51:47.600
that their role there
in calling attention.

00:51:47.600 --> 00:51:49.690
You know, they're not
going to be as important

00:51:49.690 --> 00:51:51.490
in major power geopolitics.

00:51:51.490 --> 00:51:54.780
They can, there can
be some things.

00:51:54.780 --> 00:51:56.740
Secondly is in this
philanthropy statesmanship.

00:51:56.740 --> 00:51:59.050
If you watch the role of the
Gates Foundation has played.

00:51:59.050 --> 00:52:01.840
You know, one of the
chapters in the book is

00:52:01.840 --> 00:52:04.890
on Gro Harlem Brundtland who,
she was the Prime Minister

00:52:04.890 --> 00:52:08.210
of Norway, but she's in there
for her international role.

00:52:08.210 --> 00:52:10.900
First in chairing the
World Commission on,

00:52:10.900 --> 00:52:12.760
on Sustainable Development
in the '80s.

00:52:12.760 --> 00:52:14.640
That took the term
and the thinking

00:52:14.640 --> 00:52:17.820
of sustainable development,
you know, into the mainstream.

00:52:17.820 --> 00:52:20.840
And, and you could be
green in both ways, right?

00:52:20.840 --> 00:52:23.050
Both for environment
and for money.

00:52:23.050 --> 00:52:27.420
And then she took over the WHO
in '90s and really reformed it.

00:52:27.420 --> 00:52:30.010
Got it paying more attention
to a variety of issues.

00:52:30.010 --> 00:52:32.560
And then unfortunately,
other leaders let it go.

00:52:32.560 --> 00:52:34.730
I think that's where
foundations come in.

00:52:34.730 --> 00:52:36.040
I think in the case
of the [inaudible]

00:52:36.040 --> 00:52:40.100
and others is the
WHO's spun its wheels,

00:52:40.100 --> 00:52:41.930
the Gates Foundation and others.

00:52:41.930 --> 00:52:43.940
You know, Doctors without
Borders and others got

00:52:43.940 --> 00:52:45.240
in there and did things.

00:52:45.240 --> 00:52:48.330
So those are two areas:
environment, three.

00:52:48.330 --> 00:52:50.270
Environment and the
sustainability of global health

00:52:50.270 --> 00:52:52.060
and environment and
human rights.

00:52:52.060 --> 00:52:54.960
Where I think we need
you know again the notion

00:52:54.960 --> 00:52:56.890
of what governments are
unable and willing to do.

00:52:56.890 --> 00:53:00.640
And to push to get
governments to act.

