00:53:18.360 --> 00:53:25.850
But it seems to me if time and
personal attention are needed.

00:53:25.850 --> 00:53:28.070
There's also more
heat and light coming

00:53:28.070 --> 00:53:31.100
from putting those
leadership relationships

00:53:31.100 --> 00:53:34.040
under a microscope
or into blogs.

00:53:34.040 --> 00:53:37.060
[Laughter] Almost immediately,
and has that changed the ability

00:53:37.060 --> 00:53:39.950
to make them possible?

00:53:39.950 --> 00:53:41.250
&gt;&gt; Dr. Bruce Jentleson: I think,

00:53:41.250 --> 00:53:42.780
I think it's added
the complication.

00:53:42.780 --> 00:53:44.320
Particularly like
the time factor.

00:53:44.320 --> 00:53:47.420
It's very hard to
control message.

00:53:47.420 --> 00:53:49.980
Or sometimes, you know, I know
you make a policy decision,

00:53:49.980 --> 00:53:51.280
you've got to get out quickly.

00:53:51.280 --> 00:53:54.300
And sometimes, you know, any
of us know from any situation

00:53:54.300 --> 00:53:57.030
that a quick decision
may not be, you know,

00:53:57.030 --> 00:53:58.830
well thought through,
well researched.

00:53:58.830 --> 00:54:01.590
I, I, I you know, but
again I go back to.

00:54:01.590 --> 00:54:04.350
And I try to build up to
the U.S.-China opening.

00:54:04.350 --> 00:54:08.180
And the Red China, and I go
back to the Soviet Union,

00:54:08.180 --> 00:54:10.200
and I go back on
Rabin and others.

00:54:10.200 --> 00:54:13.010
And who would have
thought Mandela, you know,

00:54:13.010 --> 00:54:14.460
would get out of prison?

00:54:14.460 --> 00:54:17.870
That the South African political
transformation would be peaceful

00:54:17.870 --> 00:54:19.170
and democratic?

00:54:19.170 --> 00:54:24.010
That he, after 27 years in
prison, plenty of reason to,

00:54:24.010 --> 00:54:26.410
you know, be resentful.

00:54:26.410 --> 00:54:29.490
So I, I don't think our
current situation precludes it.

00:54:29.490 --> 00:54:31.010
I really don't at all.

00:54:31.010 --> 00:54:33.230
I think people in
some ways are anxious

00:54:33.230 --> 00:54:36.440
for vision and leadership.

00:54:36.440 --> 00:54:39.300
I acknowledge that in some
respect social psychologists

00:54:39.300 --> 00:54:42.500
will say that appealing
to people's fear

00:54:42.500 --> 00:54:46.520
and anxiety psychologically
can always be easier.

00:54:46.520 --> 00:54:48.270
Than to their hope
and aspirations.

00:54:48.270 --> 00:54:51.180
And that's an inherent
psychological problem.

00:54:51.180 --> 00:54:53.210
But I feel like with everything
we're going through now,

00:54:53.210 --> 00:54:55.500
I think, I actually think
that, that, that the,

00:54:55.500 --> 00:54:57.590
that the table's being set.

00:54:57.590 --> 00:54:59.860
You know for that sort of thing.

00:54:59.860 --> 00:55:01.410
And, and so I, I hold out.

00:55:01.410 --> 00:55:03.400
And I don't think it's naive.

00:55:03.400 --> 00:55:05.840
I think it's based on, on that.

00:55:05.840 --> 00:55:07.450
You know, based on the
research I did and,

00:55:07.450 --> 00:55:10.840
and the intractability of
many of these problems.

00:55:10.840 --> 00:55:14.480
You know, I'm not betting my
next non-subprime mortgage

00:55:14.480 --> 00:55:17.520
payment that it's going
to happen you know soon.

00:55:17.520 --> 00:55:21.180
But I think there's, there's
an analytic and strategy path

00:55:21.180 --> 00:55:22.520
to make those kinds
of things happen.

00:55:22.520 --> 00:55:24.290
In a variety of areas.

00:55:24.290 --> 00:55:27.720
Environment's a good
example where, you know,

00:55:27.720 --> 00:55:30.770
you read a magazine from the
real estate industry now.

00:55:30.770 --> 00:55:32.690
They sound like my
old boss, Al Gore.

00:55:32.690 --> 00:55:35.080
Right? Because they have
all these, you know,

00:55:35.080 --> 00:55:38.560
hotels on the shoreline of
Miami Beach and elsewhere.

00:55:38.560 --> 00:55:43.640
And you know, and so the
business community has begun

00:55:43.640 --> 00:55:44.940
to see that.

00:55:44.940 --> 00:55:46.920
We have a political issue in
our country, you know, that,

00:55:46.920 --> 00:55:48.230
that's been problematic there.

00:55:48.230 --> 00:55:49.590
But you begin to see change.

00:55:49.590 --> 00:55:52.290
And then you need leadership
that can tap that change.

00:55:52.290 --> 00:55:54.460
That's that person and moment.

00:55:54.460 --> 00:55:56.120
You know, with all
due respect to Al Gore

00:55:56.120 --> 00:55:59.350
who I think was extraordinarily
insightful.

00:55:59.350 --> 00:56:01.950
You know, the moment
in 1992 or even 2000

00:56:01.950 --> 00:56:04.640
on the environment
it just wasn't there.

00:56:04.640 --> 00:56:07.190
Right? And so it's where
these two intersect.

00:56:07.190 --> 00:56:10.140
How and when they intersect
isn't always predictable.

00:56:10.140 --> 00:56:12.880
But I think on some of these
issues, we're really at a moment

00:56:12.880 --> 00:56:15.200
where people would
respond to leaders

00:56:15.200 --> 00:56:17.790
that they believe have
this authenticity.

00:56:17.790 --> 00:56:21.790
And a vision that you know
that is somewhat reassuring.

00:56:21.790 --> 00:56:23.200
That, the, that you know,

00:56:23.200 --> 00:56:26.420
that change can lead
to better futures.

00:56:26.420 --> 00:56:27.720
&gt;&gt; John Haskell: We have time

00:56:27.720 --> 00:56:29.580
for one more question,
if we have it?

00:56:29.580 --> 00:56:31.970
This gentleman over
here, last question.

00:56:34.250 --> 00:56:35.550
&gt;&gt; Audience Question: I wanted

00:56:35.550 --> 00:56:36.850
to ask a little bit
about Irving Babbitt.

00:56:36.850 --> 00:56:39.070
I want to see if you
think there's a connection

00:56:39.070 --> 00:56:42.580
between a strong moral
character, both in the citizenry

00:56:42.580 --> 00:56:44.850
and of the, these statesman.

00:56:44.850 --> 00:56:46.670
That correlates to
good statesmanship?

00:56:46.670 --> 00:56:47.970
&gt;&gt; Dr. Bruce Jentleson: What
was the first thing you wanted

00:56:47.970 --> 00:56:49.270
to ask about who?

00:56:49.270 --> 00:56:50.570
&gt;&gt; Audience Question:
Oh, Irving Babbitt.

00:56:50.570 --> 00:56:51.870
I'm just channeling him.

00:56:51.870 --> 00:56:53.960
&gt;&gt; Dr. Bruce Jentleson:
Okay, so I use the term

00:56:53.960 --> 00:56:58.080
in the book personal capital in
which moral capital is a subset.

00:56:58.080 --> 00:56:59.380
So it's hard to talk

00:56:59.380 --> 00:57:02.100
about Kissinger [inaudible]
having moral capital, right?

00:57:02.100 --> 00:57:04.020
But they had personal capital.

00:57:04.020 --> 00:57:06.050
Mandela had moral capital,

00:57:06.050 --> 00:57:07.700
[inaudible] in that
role had moral capital.

00:57:07.700 --> 00:57:09.450
Rabin had enormous
moral capital.

00:57:09.450 --> 00:57:14.960
And so I sort of define it as
qualities that the person has

00:57:14.960 --> 00:57:19.250
that are not just a function
of the position they occupy.

00:57:19.250 --> 00:57:21.870
The two Northern
Irish women had it.

00:57:21.870 --> 00:57:24.090
You know, Walesa
had it as a worker.

00:57:24.090 --> 00:57:25.660
And that's enormously important.

00:57:25.660 --> 00:57:28.600
There's an authenticity
thing that people, you know,

00:57:28.600 --> 00:57:30.520
the average person wants
to know that you know,

00:57:30.520 --> 00:57:32.800
you really are what
you say you are.

00:57:32.800 --> 00:57:35.830
Having worked in quite a few
presidential campaigns and gone

00:57:35.830 --> 00:57:38.470
through the consultant as
the perfect resume, you know.

00:57:38.470 --> 00:57:42.010
I think that, that
these qualities--

00:57:42.010 --> 00:57:43.540
and so when I talk
about leadership.

00:57:43.540 --> 00:57:46.000
You know, I use this broad
sense of personal capital.

00:57:46.000 --> 00:57:49.100
And it is really important
for transformational change.

00:57:49.100 --> 00:57:50.730
And, and it's not necessarily.

00:57:50.730 --> 00:57:52.820
You know, there are very
few leaders in the book

00:57:52.820 --> 00:57:55.450
who were like, you
know, LeBron James,

00:57:55.450 --> 00:57:57.180
you know coming out immediately.

00:57:57.180 --> 00:57:58.480
Or Mozart as a young person.

00:57:58.480 --> 00:58:01.090
They emerge through
their life experiences.

00:58:01.090 --> 00:58:02.390
And they get to that point.

00:58:02.390 --> 00:58:04.420
Mandela's probably the closest
because he you know came

00:58:04.420 --> 00:58:07.360
out of this particular,
you know, upbringing.

00:58:07.360 --> 00:58:09.550
But the others are you know
who would have thunk it

00:58:09.550 --> 00:58:12.670
at an earlier point in
their, in their lives, okay?

